		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Eutrapelus, in maximis negotiis, actor maior: apud
						summas mundi personas,
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Eutrapelus"/>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						legatus superior:
						in molestissimis casib[us] priuatis, publicis, aut etiam
						in tristissimis calamitatibus,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						vel pra[e]sens remediu[m], vel
						magnifica patientia: ( festiuissim&egrave; ferendo, 
						pulcherrimam pra[e] se ) victoria[m]: et omnium
						semper cordatissimus. Nunq[uam] visus trepidare, aut 
						despondere generosu[m] animu[m]; aut languere defessus; 
						aut frigere ignauus;
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						aut in salebris ha[e]rere; aut
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						vllo modo Superari; aut aliqua deniq[ue] parte turbari.
						Sed quauis negotioru[m], casuum, periculorum mole,
						semper ingentior.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<language ident="IT">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Vnico risoluto del mondo.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				In the greatest affairs, Eutrapelus is a greater actor, among the highest people of the world,
				a superior officer. In the most both tiresome private or public cases, or even in the saddest 
				calamities, he has a prompt remedy, or magnificent patience.  In a most lively manner,
				he carries a most beautiful victory before him and is always most sensible.
				His noble soul never seems to be afraid or despondent; nor does he languish in exhausation,
				or lack vigor in laziness, or hesitate in an uneven manner of speaking. He is never surpassed
				in any way; nor, finally, is he ever disturbed in any part.
				But he is always greater than any mass of affairs, cases, or dangers. The uniquely resolute [man] of the world.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						In viro Singulari, decet Singula esse Singularia.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				In a singular man, singular things must be single.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
